{"id":"1911.01061","submitter":"Frederik vom Ende","authors":"Frederik vom Ende, Gunther Dirr","title":"The $d$-Majorization Polytope","comments":"35 pages, 2 figures, revised version. Re-submitted to Linear Algebra\n  and its Applications","journal-ref":"Linear Algebra Appl., 649 (2022) 152-185","doi":"10.1016/j.laa.2022.05.005","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math-ph math.FA math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate geometric and topological properties of $d$-majorization -- a\ngeneralization of classical majorization to positive weight vectors $d \\in\n\\mathbb{R}^n$. In particular, we derive a new, simplified characterization of\n$d$-majorization which allows us to work out a halfspace description of the\ncorresponding $d$-majorization polytopes. That is, we write the set of all\nvectors which are $d$-majorized by some given vector $y \\in \\mathbb{R}^n$ as an\nintersection of finitely many half spaces, i.e. as solutions to an inequality\nof the type $Mx\\leq b$. Here $b$ depends on $y$ while $M$ can be chosen\nindependently of $y$. This description lets us prove continuity of the\n$d$-majorization polytope (jointly with respect to $d$ and $y$) and,\nfurthermore, lets us fully characterize its extreme points. Interestingly, for\n$y\\geq 0$ one of these extreme points classically majorizes every other element\nof the $d$-majorization polytope. Moreover, we show that the induced preorder\nstructure on $\\mathbb{R}^n$ admits minimal and maximal elements. While the\nformer are always unique the latter are unique if and only if they correspond\nto the unique minimal entry of the $d$-vector.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Nov 2019 07:38:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 10 Mar 2020 10:15:46 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 19 Oct 2020 14:31:55 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sun, 12 Dec 2021 13:19:39 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Fri, 6 May 2022 14:31:06 GMT"}],"update