{"id":"1911.01159","submitter":"Claudius Hubig","authors":"C. Hubig, A. Bohrdt, M. Knap, F. Grusdt and J. I. Cirac","title":"Evaluation of time-dependent correlators after a local quench in iPEPS:\n  hole motion in the t-J model","comments":"12 pages, 5 figures, minor revision requested by SciPost Physics","journal-ref":"SciPost Phys. 8, 021 (2020)","doi":"10.21468/SciPostPhys.8.2.021","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el quant-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  Infinite projected entangled pair states (iPEPS) provide a convenient\nvariational description of infinite, translationally-invariant two-dimensional\nquantum states. However, the simulation of local excitations is not directly\npossible due to the translationally-invariant ansatz. Furthermore, as iPEPS are\neither identical or orthogonal, expectation values between different states as\nrequired during the evaluation of non-equal-time correlators are ill-defined.\nHere, we show that by introducing auxiliary states on each site, it becomes\npossible to simulate both local excitations and evaluate non-equal-time\ncorrelators in an iPEPS setting under real-time evolution. We showcase the\nmethod by simulating the t-J model after a single hole has been placed in the\nhalf-filled antiferromagnetic background and evaluating both return\nprobabilities and spin correlation functions, as accessible in quantum gas\nmicroscopes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Nov 2019 12:33:03 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 14 Jan 2020 13:33:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-02-12"}
{"id":"1911.01160","submitter":"Alexander Szameit","authors":"Gerard Queralto, Mark Kremer, Lukas J. Maczewsky, Matthias Heinrich,\n  Jordi Mompart, Veronica Ahufinger, and Alexander Szameit","title":"Topological state engineering via supersymmetric transformations","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The quest to explore new techniques for the manipulation of topological\nstates simultaneously promotes a deeper understanding of topological physics,\nand is essential in identifying new ways to harness their unique features.\nHere, we examine the potential of supersymmetric (SUSY) transformations to\nsystematically address, alter and reconfigure the topological properties of a\nsystem. To this end, we theoretically and experimentally study the changes that\ntopologically protected states in photonic lattices undergo as SUSY\ntransformations are applied to their host system. In particular, we show how\nSUSY-induced phase transitions can selectively suspend and re-establish\ntopological protection of specific states. Furthermore, we reveal how\nunderstanding the interplay between internal symmetries and the symmetry\nconstraints of supersymmetric transformations provides a roadmap to directly\naccess the desirable topological properties of a system. Our findings pave the\nway for establishing SUSY-inspired techniques as a powerful and versatile tool\nfor topological state engineering.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 4 Nov 2019 12:34:47 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-05"}
